Question: What improvements would you like to see in these cultural funding programs?

Response ID: resp_1088
Response Text: 1) Easier access and support for applicants who don't speak English. 2) An application that does not require applicants to have a graduate school education understanding of academic ideas of diversity and inclusion. 3) Broader definition of diversity that doesn't create a strict hierarchy of need. Queer and disability-led organizations seemed to not be as valued in the current funding programs compared to racial and ethnic diversity. Obviously, there is a deep need for support to organizations that are led by BIPOC individuals. But there is also a need for the Queer and disability community to be seen in these funding programs. 4) Another improvement would be reevaluating the review panels to ensure there is a deeper understanding of the community, its members, and its history. 5) Assuring that these programs go to organizations that are actual art practitioners. I noticed that there were organizations who received the highest level of funding that are non-arts non-profits or organizations that maybe have one art camp. Arts funding should go to organizations that produce, make or create art in our community, and/or serve artists. While noble, a single arts camp, put on by a massive non-profit organization that already has deep pockets, does not in reality support our creative community. 5) Better access to lower-level funding opportunities for organizations.

